Answers to Frequently Asked Questions

  <Alt>+<Space> may be used instead of the <Space> character: it is printed
as a space, but is not treated as such by the text processing functions.
This may be useful to take advantage of some special features of the
PostScript column alignment mode (e.g. to add small spaces at the
beginning of a column), to prevent automatic word-wrap where it may
interrupt words which should remain on the same line, or to prevent
printer justification from putting too much space between two words which
are logically joined (e.g. a number and its measurement unit). When
printing with proportional characters, any sequence of space characters at
the beginning of a line is corrected as specified by the "Proportional
adjust" value. An <Alt>+<Space> character at the beginning of any such
line would prevent this.

  It is much more convenient to use <Amiga>+<F> and <Amiga>+<G> to
respectively set and strip style information (e.g. italic). These
attributes, as well as paragraph settings, are better set after the text
to which they refer has been typed. Personal Write allows the user to
manually delete style control tags, like "End Italic". If this is done by
mistake, <Amiga>+<G> can be used to delete the other control sequence
without affecting the text.

  Search and Replace functions allow for the paragraph sign (<Return> key)
to be searched and replaced. <Ctrl>+<J> can be used for this purpose in
all string gadgets, after the Text Gadget Filter setting in the Amiga
IControl Preferences has been disabled.

  Section 1.3 of the handbook contains more answers to common questions.


